						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="bold">King: Vīrarājēndra i.e., Kullōttuṅgachōḷa III Year 5: 1183 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription records the gift of four golden ornaments weighing together 220 1/2 <hi rend="italic">kaḻañju</hi>, 2 <hi rend="italic">mañjāḍi</hi> and 4 <hi rend="italic">mā</hi> of gold. They consisted of upper garment <hi rend="italic">(tiru-uttiriyam)</hi>, amulet <hi rend="italic">(tirumāṅgalya kārigai)</hi>, an arch doorway resembling a crocodile <hi rend="italic">(makara tōraṇam)</hi> and belt of gold <hi rend="italic">(tiruppaṭṭigai)</hi>, by Tayinallaḷ <hi rend="italic">alias</hi> Śivakāmasundarimāṇikkam, daughter of Umaiāḻvi <hi rend="italic">alias</hi> Āgāravallanaṅgai, the <hi rend="italic">dēvaraḍiyāḷ</hi> of the god Tugumāmaṇi-nāyaṉār.</p>						

						</summary>
